-- Sub-Saharan Africa Stocks: Kenya Airways, Total Kenya Are Active
-- B y   S t e p h e n   G u n n i o n   a n d   R e n e e   B o n o r c h i s
-- 2011-12-19T16:31:57Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-12-19/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-kenya-airways-total-kenya-are-active.html
Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index (SEMDEX)  declined
for a second day, slipping less than 0.1 percent to 1,854.98 by
the end of trading in Port Louis, the capital.  Kenya’s  All-Share Index (NSEASI)  dropped 0.4 percent to 54.33 by the
close in Nairobi. The  Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index (NGSEINDX) 
was unchanged at 20,025.94 by the end of trade in Lagos,
according to a  statement  on the bourse’s website. The
 FTSE/Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  declined 0.9 percent to 830.55 by the
4 p.m. close in Windhoek. The  Ghana Stock Exchange Composite
Index  fell 2.2 percent to 919.64 by the 3 p.m. close in Accra, a
second day of losses.  The following shares were active in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Kenya Airways Ltd. (KNAL)  , sub-Saharan Africa’s third-
biggest airline, retreated for the first time in five days,
slipping 0.3 percent to 19.9 shillings. The company will ask
labor unions and the government for permission to hire more
foreign airline captains as it expands its fleet, Business Daily
said, citing Chief Executive Officer Titus Naikuni.  Total Kenya Ltd. (TKNL)  , a local unit of  Total SA (FP) ,
advanced for the first time in three days, adding 0.7 percent to
14.45 shillings. Oil recovered from near its lowest in more than
six weeks in New York as advancing equity markets eased concern
that European government measures will be unable to stem the
debt crisis.  To contact the reporters on this story:
